<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-03-10T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-03-10T12:00:00-05:00" n="190" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d190">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1571</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-10T17:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">March, 10, 1915, 5 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 8 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1762. Your 1182, February 24.<note n="1" xml:id="d190fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_122">p.
                                    122</ref>.</note> Much inquiry has failed to show that any order
                                has been issued by the British Government to merchant vessels to arm
                                themselves; but there is reason to believe that the Government has
                                permitted arming when ships have asked. There is no evidence that I
                                have yet found, however, that any transatlantic British merchantmen
                                have been armed. And all the arming that may have been done has been
                                done since the German submarine “blockade” began and it has been
                                done with reference to German submarine attacks.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>